+# Connectivity Package Spec
+
+Date: 2026-04-11
+
+## Purpose
+
+This document defines `@relay-assistant/connectivity` as a first-class SDK layer.
+
+The package should own the internal signaling semantics that let multiple assistant subsystems converge quickly without collapsing into generic chat, transport leakage, or product-specific orchestration code.
+
+It sits:
+
+- above Relay foundation transport and delivery primitives
+- beside `@relay-assistant/coordination`
+- adjacent to `@relay-assistant/routing`
+- below product-specific specialist behavior in Sage, MSD, NightCTO, and future assistants
+
+## Core Thesis
+
+Assistant systems increasingly have several sophisticated subsystems active at once:
+
+- coordinator/orchestrator
+- memory and context retrieval
+- proactive watchers
+- review or planning specialists
+- synthesis or response generation
+- policy and approval gates
+
+Those subsystems do not just need transport. They need disciplined signaling.
+
+Transport answers "how did bytes get delivered."
+
+Coordination answers "what work is assigned to which specialist and how do we synthesize the outcome."
+
+Connectivity answers "what minimal, structured signals should move between active subsystems so the whole assistant can allocate attention, resolve uncertainty, escalate correctly, and stop wasting cycles."
+
+That distinction is important because a system can have:
+
+- transport without useful convergence
+- coordination without efficient local signaling
+- signaling without needing product-specific orchestration rules
+
+`@relay-assistant/connectivity` exists to make that middle layer explicit.
+
+## Why Connectivity Is Distinct
+
+### Distinct from coordination
+
+Coordination owns the work graph:
+
+- who is responsible
+- which specialists are engaged
+- what the delegation plan is
+- how outputs are synthesized into one assistant answer
+
+Connectivity owns the signaling policy that flows through that work graph:
+
+- attention and salience
+- confidence and uncertainty
+- conflict and consensus
+- handoff readiness
+- escalation urgency
+- "do not interrupt" or "not worth propagating" decisions
+
+Coordination is about task structure.
+
+Connectivity is about signal structure.
+
+A coordinator may decide to ask three specialists for input. Connectivity decides whether a new piece of evidence should:
+
+- narrowcast to one specialist
+- broadcast to all active participants
+- escalate to the coordinator immediately
+- remain local and silent
+
+If coordination owns work topology, connectivity owns information flow discipline inside that topology.
+
+### Distinct from Relay transport
+
+Relay foundation owns:
+
+- normalized inbound/outbound events
+- channels, sessions, relaycast, and message delivery
+- auth, webhook verification, and provider integration
+- scheduler substrate and wake-up plumbing
+
+Connectivity must not care whether a signal traveled through:
+
+- an in-process queue
+- a local async runtime
+- relaycast/channels
+- a cloud event bus
+
+Its contracts should be transport-agnostic and semantic.
+
+Relay transport says:
+
+- deliver this envelope to destination X
+
+Connectivity says:
+
+- this is a `conflict` signal
+- its audience is `coordinator`
+- it expires after synthesis step N
+- it should interrupt current work
+- it should not be shown to the user
+
+That semantic layer belongs in the assistant SDK, not in foundation transport.
+
+## Practical Brain-Inspired Framing
+
+The package should use a neural analogy only where it improves design clarity.
+
+Useful framing:
+
+- neurons are not passing essays to each other; they pass compact signals
+- most local state stays local unless a threshold is crossed
+- strong signals recruit broader network attention
+- inhibitory signals are as important as excitatory ones
+- convergence depends on sparse, high-value communication rather than unrestricted chatter
+
+In assistant terms:
+
+- specialists should keep most intermediate reasoning private
+- only decision-relevant deltas should be emitted
+- high-salience evidence should recruit the right downstream components quickly
+- low-value chatter should be suppressed
+- explicit "hold", "mute", or "already resolved" signals should prevent waste
+
+This is not a claim that the package should mimic biology literally.
+
+The practical takeaway is:
+
+- prefer compact signals over conversational transcripts
+- prefer thresholded propagation over indiscriminate fanout
+- prefer local resolution before global escalation
+- treat attention as scarce
+- treat interruption as expensive
+
+That framing is useful because multi-subsystem assistants fail in the same way noisy distributed systems fail:
+
+- too many low-value messages
+- late escalation of high-risk issues
+- repeated rediscovery of already-known facts
+- poor conflict surfacing
+- excessive broadcast
+
+Connectivity should correct those failure modes.
+
+## Design Goals
+
+The package should help assistant subsystems:
+
+- converge faster with fewer tokens and fewer interrupts
+- surface the right uncertainty early
+- avoid redundant specialist work
+- preserve one coherent assistant identity
+- remain transport-agnostic
+- align with workforce-influenced routing without becoming the routing package
+
+The package should not become:
+
+- a generic message bus
+- a transport SDK
+- a product workflow engine
+- a specialist registry
+- a hosted-only event system
+
+## Signal Categories Connectivity Should Own
+
+These are the main message classes the package should define.
+
+### 1. Attention and salience signals
+
+Use these when a subsystem believes some fact or event deserves attention outside its local scope.
+
+Examples:
+
+- new evidence materially changes likely outcome
+- a user intent appears under-served by current active specialists
+- a policy-relevant event should preempt normal synthesis
+- a stale or unresolved thread becomes high priority
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `attention.requested`
+- `attention.raised`
+- `attention.dismissed`
+- `salience.delta`
+
+### 2. Confidence and uncertainty signals
+
+Use these to propagate how stable or unstable a subsystem's local conclusion is.
+
+Examples:
+
+- memory retrieval is weak or conflicting
+- a reviewer is highly confident a plan is unsafe
+- proactive evidence is too thin for autonomous action
+- synthesis is blocked on missing facts
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `confidence.high`
+- `confidence.medium`
+- `confidence.low`
+- `uncertainty.blocker`
+- `uncertainty.watch`
+
+### 3. Conflict and consensus signals
+
+Use these when outputs disagree or begin to converge.
+
+Examples:
+
+- one specialist recommends escalation, another recommends silence
+- memory and live context disagree
+- two reviewers independently identify the same issue
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `conflict.detected`
+- `conflict.resolved`
+- `consensus.emerging`
+- `consensus.reached`
+
+### 4. Handoff and readiness signals
+
+Use these to avoid polling and vague orchestration.
+
+Examples:
+
+- a subsystem has produced synthesis-ready output
+- a specialist cannot proceed without more scope
+- a partial result is good enough for downstream use
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `handoff.ready`
+- `handoff.blocked`
+- `handoff.declined`
+- `result.partial`
+- `result.final`
+
+### 5. Escalation and interruption signals
+
+Use these for urgent state changes that should cut through normal flow.
+
+Examples:
+
+- security or policy risk detected
+- user-visible deadline risk
+- proactive action should be stopped
+- a runtime failure invalidates current plan
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `escalation.immediate`
+- `escalation.required`
+- `interrupt.now`
+- `interrupt.suggested`
+- `abort.current_path`
+
+### 6. Budget and verbosity signals
+
+Use these to preserve efficiency and avoid over-communication.
+
+Examples:
+
+- downstream consumer wants short delta-only updates
+- current mode does not justify broad discussion
+- this branch is in low-latency mode and should suppress noncritical traffic
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `budget.tight`
+- `budget.normal`
+- `verbosity.delta_only`
+- `verbosity.summary_ok`
+- `verbosity.full_context_required`
+
+### 7. Memory and persistence relevance signals
+
+Use these when a subsystem believes information should or should not be preserved beyond the local step.
+
+Examples:
+
+- a finding should be promoted to workspace memory
+- an observation is ephemeral and should not persist
+- a signal should be attached to session state for follow-up engines
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `memory.promote_candidate`
+- `memory.session_relevant`
+- `memory.workspace_relevant`
+- `memory.do_not_store`
+
+### 8. Closure and silence signals
+
+These are critical. Efficient systems need explicit negative propagation rules.
+
+Examples:
+
+- a topic is resolved and should stop generating downstream work
+- a low-confidence suspicion was disproven
+- a consumer has already incorporated the latest relevant state
+
+Candidate signal kinds:
+
+- `close.resolved`
+- `close.superseded`
+- `silent.not_worth_propagating`
+- `silent.already_known`
+- `silent.local_only`
+
+## Message Shape Principles
+
+Connectivity messages should be:
+
+- compact
+- typed
+- non-conversational
+- scoped
+- interrupt-aware
+- expiration-aware
+
+A signal should usually contain:
+
+- `kind`
+- `source`
+- `audience`
+- `subject`
+- `salience`
+- `confidence`
+- `urgency`
+- `summary`
+- `evidenceRef` or compact evidence payload
+- `recommendedAction`
+- `ttlMs` or lifecycle boundary
+
+Most signals should not carry long freeform text. They should carry a small summary plus references to richer state held elsewhere.
+
+## Delivery Posture: Narrowcast, Broadcast, Escalate, or Stay Silent
+
+This package should make those four decisions first-class.
+
+### Narrowcast
+
+Use narrowcast when:
+
+- one specialist is clearly the best next consumer
+- the signal is domain-specific rather than globally relevant
+- interruption cost is nontrivial
+- the coordinator does not need to intervene yet
+
+Examples:
+
+- memory retrieval confidence dropped for one synthesis step
+- code-review risk belongs only to the security reviewer
+- a proactive watcher found evidence relevant only to the follow-up engine
+
+Rule:
+
+- default to narrowcast unless a broader audience is clearly justified
+
+### Broadcast
+
+Use broadcast when:
+
+- multiple active subsystems need the same state to avoid divergence
+- the signal affects the shared frame for current synthesis
+- consensus formation benefits from shared visibility
+
+Examples:
+
+- user intent was reclassified
+- policy mode changed
+- critical workspace context invalidates several active branches
+- a synthesizer requests one common decision boundary from all specialists
+
+Rule:
+
+- broadcast only shared-frame changes, not raw intermediate reasoning
+
+### Escalate
+
+Use escalation when:
+
+- risk is high and delay is costly
+- a conflict cannot be resolved locally
+- policy, safety, or user trust is implicated
+- normal synthesis would hide or dilute the issue
+- a subsystem believes the current route/model/plan is materially wrong
+
+Examples:
+
+- a security specialist finds a likely credential leak
+- memory evidence conflicts with live user instructions in a policy-relevant way
+- a specialist concludes that silent continuation would create a misleading user answer
+
+Rule:
+
+- escalation should be rare, explicit, and interrupt-capable
+
+### Stay silent
+
+Stay silent when:
+
+- the information is local bookkeeping
+- no downstream decision changes
+- confidence is too low and no threshold is crossed
+- another signal already communicated the relevant delta
+- the recipient cannot act on it
+
+Examples:
+
+- a subsystem is exploring a branch that has not produced a stable result
+- repeated evidence does not materially change prior belief
+- a detail is only needed inside one component's internal scoring logic
+
+Rule:
+
+- silence is success, not failure, when propagation would not improve convergence
+
+## Propagation Heuristics
+
+The package should make signal propagation threshold-based.
+
+Useful default heuristics:
+
+- propagate only deltas, not full state snapshots, unless explicitly requested
+- prefer one-hop delivery to the likely decision-maker
+- if a signal is unresolved after one hop, allow coordinator escalation
+- suppress duplicates within a bounded time or synthesis window
+- attach decay or expiration to speculative signals
+- require stronger salience for broadcast than for narrowcast
+- require stronger urgency for interrupting an in-flight synthesis than for queueing a note
+
+This gives consumers a practical baseline without forcing product teams to reinvent suppression logic.
+
+## How Connectivity Helps Sophisticated Subsystems Converge Efficiently
+
+This package should help convergence in six concrete ways.
+
+### 1. Shared signal vocabulary
+
+Subsystems should not invent incompatible local meanings for "important", "blocked", or "done".
+
+Connectivity gives them a common typed vocabulary, which reduces translation overhead and brittle ad hoc glue.
+
+### 2. Early conflict surfacing
+
+Specialists often disagree before the coordinator notices.
+
+Connectivity should make conflict and uncertainty signals cheap to emit and cheap to recognize so synthesis can adapt before a full fan-in stall occurs.
+
+### 3. Efficient fan-in
+
+Instead of waiting for every subsystem to submit a narrative report, the coordinator should be able to react to:
+
+- blocker
+- high-confidence convergence
+- urgent policy issue
+- synthesis-ready partial result
+
+That reduces latency and token waste.
+
+### 4. Reduced redundant work
+
+If a subsystem can emit:
+
+- `silent.already_known`
+- `consensus.reached`
+- `close.resolved`
+
+then other subsystems can stop searching or stop refreshing stale hypotheses.
+
+### 5. Better interrupt discipline
+
+Without a shared signaling layer, everything urgent becomes either a hard interrupt or a hidden log line.
+
+Connectivity should provide a graded path:
+
+- queued note
+- attention raise
+- escalation required
+- immediate interrupt
+
+### 6. Cleaner synthesis inputs
+
+Synthesis should consume compact, typed signals and linked evidence rather than sprawling internal chat. That gives the coordinator a better chance of producing one coherent assistant answer with fewer contradictory fragments.
+
+## Interaction with Routing and Workforce-Influenced Model Choice
+
+Connectivity should interact with `@relay-assistant/routing`, but it should not absorb routing ownership.
+
+### Routing owns
+
+- model selection
+- depth/latency/cost posture
+- specialist engagement policy
+- workforce-aligned workload profiles, persona tiers, and response modes
+
+### Connectivity owns
+
+- what active components should communicate once engaged
+- how much signal detail is justified under the current route
+- whether a route should be challenged through escalation
+
+### Practical interaction pattern
+
+Routing should be able to publish mode constraints that connectivity respects, for example:
+
+- low-latency route implies `verbosity.delta_only`
+- deep-analysis route tolerates broader consensus-building
+- low-cost route raises broadcast threshold
+- premium or high-risk route allows earlier escalation and more explicit uncertainty propagation
+
+Connectivity should be able to emit routing-relevant signals, for example:
+
+- `uncertainty.blocker` suggesting a deeper model tier is warranted
+- `conflict.detected` suggesting more specialist participation
+- `budget.tight` indicating the current branch should stop broad fanout
+- `escalation.required` indicating the current route is unsafe for the detected risk
+
+The dependency boundary should remain:
+
+- routing provides envelope and mode
+- connectivity governs communication behavior inside that envelope
+
+This aligns cleanly with workforce concepts.
+
+`workforce` already has prior art around workload routing, personas, and profiles. Connectivity should not recreate those concepts. It should consume the routing outcome as context and adapt communication policy accordingly.
+
+Example:
+
+- routing decides this task is `fast/high-value`
+- coordination engages only coordinator plus one specialist
+- connectivity applies narrowcast-first, low-verbosity, high-threshold broadcast behavior
+
+Another example:
+
+- routing decides this task is `deep/high-risk`
+- coordination engages multiple specialists
+- connectivity lowers thresholds for uncertainty sharing and conflict surfacing while preserving duplicate suppression
+
+## Likely First Exportable Interfaces
+
+The first interfaces should be small, typed, and easy to implement locally.
+
+### Core types
+
+```ts
